Ogilvie|title=Cambridge Ancient History: Volume 7, Part 2, 2nd Edition| location=Cambridge|\npublisher=Cambridge University Press|lastauthoramp=y |year=2006 |orig-year=1989| isbn= 0-521-23446-8\n|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| volume =8\n| issue =22\n| pages =50\u201357\n| last =Shutt\n| first =Rowland\n| title =Polybius: A Sketch\n| journal =Greece & Rome\n| date =1938\n| jstor =642112\n|ref=harv| doi =10.1017/S001738350000588X\n}}\n\n* {{cite book|last1=Sidwell|first1=Keith C.|last2=Jones|first2=Peter V.|title=The World of Rome: An Introduction to Roman Culture|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0-521-38600-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YkgTbON-GGUC|ref=harv}}\n\n* {{Cite journal\n| volume = 34\n| issue = 4th Qtr\n| pages =432\u2013465\n| last = Tipps\n| first = G.K.\n| title = The Battle of Ecnomus\n| journal = Historia: Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Alte Geschichte\n| date = 1985\n| jstor = 4435938\n|ref=harv\n}}\n\n* {{cite book\n|last=Walbank\n|first=F.W.\n|date=1990\n|title=Polybius\n|volume =1\n|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=z7IpCahC2iMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=F.W.+Walbank&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6qMfxh6noAhUSfMAKHZ8iAaYQ6wEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=histories&f=false\n|location=Berkeley\n|publisher=University of California Press\n|page=\n|isbn= 978-0-520-06981-7\n|author-link=F. W. Walbank\n|ref=harv}}\n\n* {{cite book|last=Warmington|first=Brian|title=Carthage|publisher=Barnes & Noble, Inc|year=1993|origyear=1960|location=New York|isbn=978-1-56619-210-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G0kgaFEBb4EC|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{Cite journal\n| volume =112\n| issue =3\n| pages =350\u2013367\n| last =Biggs\n| first =T.\n| title =Primus Romanorum: Origin Stories, Fictions of Primacy, and the First Punic War\n| journal =Classical Philology\n| date =2017\n| issn =0009-837X\n| doi=10.1086/692606\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|last=T. Dexter\n|first=Hoyos\n|date=1998\n|title=Unplanned wars: The origins of the First and Second Punic Wars\n|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ja4fAAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Unplanned+wars:+The+origins+of+the+First+and+Second+Punic+Wars&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj2qPb84-rnAhW-UBUIHWMKAVoQ6wEILDAA#v=onepage&q=Unplanned%20wars%3A%20The%20origins%20of%20the%20First%20and%20Second%20Punic%20Wars&f=false\n|location=Berlin; New York\n|publisher=Walter de Gruyter\n|page=\n|isbn=978-3-11-080835-3\n|author-link=\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/1*.html Polybius on the First Punic War]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treaty Of Lutatius}}\n[[Category:241 BC]]\n[[Category:First Punic War]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Roman Republic|Lutatius]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties|Lutatius]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC treaties]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Carthage|Lutatius]]\n[[Category:3rd century BC in the Roman Republic]]\n[[Category:Treaties of ancient Rome]]\n", "name_user": "T8612", "label": "safe", "comment": "forgot the page number", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Lutatius"}
{"title_page": "Help! (film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Help!\n| image          = Helponesheet.jpg\n| image_size     = 225px\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Richard Lester]]\n| producer       = [[Walter Shenson]]\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Marc Behm]]\n* [[Charles Wood (playwright)|Charles Wood]]\n}}\n| story          = Marc Behm\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[The Beatles]]\n* [[Leo McKern]]\n* [[Eleanor Bron]]\n* [[Victor Spinetti]]\n* [[Roy Kinnear]]\n}}\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n* '''Musical Director:'''\n* [[Ken Thorne]]\n* '''Songs:'''\n* [[Lennon-McCartney]]\n* [[George Harrison]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[David Watkin (cinematographer)|David Watkin]]\n| editing        = John Victor-Smith\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* Walter Shenson Films\n* [[Apple Corps|Subafilms]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1965|7|29|UK|1965|8|11|US|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.5 million<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160202000614/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0059260/business Box Office Information for ''Help!''] [[IMDb]] via [[Internet Archive]]. Retrieved June 17, 2018.</ref>\n| gross          = $12.1 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1965/00235.php|publisher=The Numbers|title=Help!, Box Office Information|accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Help!''''' is a 1965 British [[Musical film|musical]] [[Comedy film|comedy]]-[[Adventure film|adventure]] film directed by [[Richard Lester]], starring [[the Beatles]]\u2013[[John Lennon]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[George Harrison]] and [[Ringo Starr]]\u2014and featuring [[Leo McKern]], [[Eleanor Bron]], [[Victor Spinetti]], [[John Bluthal]], [[Roy Kinnear]] and [[Patrick Cargill]]. The second film starring the Beatles following Lester's ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'', ''Help!'' sees the group struggle to record their new album while trying to protect Starr from a sinister [[cult]] and a pair of mad scientists, all of whom are obsessed with obtaining one of his rings.<ref name=\"Beatles.com\">{{cite web|title=Help!|url=http://www.beatles.com/#/films/Help|publisher=Beatles.com|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> The soundtrack was released as an album, also called ''[[Help!]]''.\n\nThe film had its Royal World Premiere at the [[London Pavilion]] Theatre in the [[West End of London]] on 29 July 1965 in the presence of [[Princess Margaret]], Countess of Snowdon and the [[Antony Charles Robert Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]]. While not reviewed at the time with the same high level of admiration as their first film, the film is regarded a half century later as being influential, including in the subsequent development of  [[music videos]].\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[File:The Beatles Trailer USHelp.jpg|left|thumb|225x225px|Screenshot of [[the Beatles]] in ''Help!'']]\nAn [[Eastern world|eastern]] [[cult]] (a parody of the [[Thuggee]] cult) is about to sacrifice a woman to the [[goddess]] [[Kali|Kali]]. They notice that she is not wearing the sacrificial ring. Instead, [[Ringo Starr]], drummer of the Beatles, has the ring, sent to him by the victim and her high priestess sister, who are both fans of the Beatles. Determined to retrieve the ring and sacrifice the girl, the great Swami, several cult members and the high priestess leave for London. After failed attempts to steal the ring without Ringo noticing, they confront him in an Indian restaurant. Ringo learns that if he be the next sacrifice if he does not give up the ring. However, the ring is stuck and he cannot take it off. The Beatles are chased around London by members of the cult. In a desperate effort to dispose of the ring, the band resorts to the bumbling efforts of a mad scientist and his assistant; when his equipment turns out to have no effect on the ring, the scientist decides that he, too, must somehow acquire it. The band runs to the Swiss Alps and narrowly escapes a trap there, thanks to the help of the high priestess, who is secretly aiding the Beatles. To stay safe, they ask for protection from Scotland Yard.  They hide in Buckingham Palace, narrowly avoiding capture by the scientist. The band runs to the Bahamas, followed by the police officers, the scientist, and the cult members. After Ringo is nearly captured, the other Beatles pose as him in order to lure out the cult members to be arrested by the police. Despite their best efforts, however, Ringo is captured by the scientist, who intends on cutting off his finger to get the ring.  The high priestess rescues Ringo by giving the scientist a shrinking solution in exchange.  The two of them dive into the ocean to escape, but Ringo cannot swim and they are both captured by the great Swami. In the end, when Ringo is about to be sacrificed, the ring suddenly comes off. He puts the ring on the great Swami who is then chased by his own cult.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[John Lennon]]     as himself \n*[[Paul McCartney]]  as himself\n*[[George Harrison]] as himself\n*[[Ringo Starr]]     as himself\n*[[Eleanor Bron]]    as Ahme\n*[[Leo McKern]]      as Clang\n*[[John Bluthal]]    as Bhuta\n*[[Patrick Cargill]] as Superintendent Gluck\n*[[Victor Spinetti]] as Foot\n*[[Roy Kinnear]]     as Algernon\n*[[Alfie Bass]]      as Doorman\n*[[Warren Mitchell]] as Abdul\n*[[Peter Copley]] as Jeweler\n*[[Bruce Lacey]] as Lawnmower\n*Durra as Belly Dancer\n*[[Mal Evans]]       as Channel Swimmer (uncredited)\n*[[Gretchen Franklin]] as Neighbor (uncredited)\n*[[Dandy Nichols]] as Neighbor (uncredited)\n*[[Jeremy Lloyd]] as Restaurant Patron (uncredited)\n*[[John Louis Mansi]] as Priest / Thug\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nAccording to interviews conducted with [[Paul McCartney]], [[George Harrison]], and [[Ringo Starr]] for ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'', director Richard Lester was given a larger budget for this film than he had for ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'', thanks to the commercial success of the latter. Thus, this feature film was in colour and was shot on several exotic foreign locations. It was also given a more extensive musical score than ''A Hard Day's Night'', provided by a full orchestra, and including pieces of well known classical music: [[Wagner]]'s ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', Act III Overture, [[Tchaikovsky]]'s \"[[1812 Overture]]\", [[Beethoven]]'s \"[[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Ninth Symphony]]\" (\"Ode to Joy\"), and, during the end credits and with their own comic vocal interpretation, [[Rossini]]'s \"[[The Barber of Seville|Barber of Seville]]\" overture. The original title for the film \u2013 only changed to ''Help!'' very near to its release \u2013 was ''Eight Arms To Hold You.''<ref>Matthews, Brian.\"Part 7,\" ''The Beatles Story'' (BBC, 1973).</ref>\n\n''Help!'' was shot in London, [[Salisbury Plain]], the [[Austria]]n [[Alps]], [[New Providence Island]] and [[Paradise Island]] in the Bahamas and [[Twickenham Film Studios]], beginning in the Bahamas on 23 February 1965. Starr commented in ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'' that they were in the Bahamas for the hot weather scenes, and therefore had to wear light clothing even though it was rather cold. Tony Bramwell, the assistant to Beatles manager Brian Epstein, stated in his book ''A Magical Mystery Tour'' that Epstein chose the Bahamas for tax reasons. According to ''The Beatles Anthology'', during the restaurant sequence filmed in early April, George began to discover [[India]]n-style music, which would be a key element in future songs such as [[Norwegian Wood (This Bird Has Flown)|\"Norwegian Wood\"]]. Filming finished on 14 April at Ailsa Avenue in [[Twickenham]].\n\nThe ski scenes were shot at [[Obertauern]], a small village in Austria. One reason this location was chosen was that the stars of the film were less likely to be recognized there than at one of the larger resorts with many British tourists. The Beatles were in Obertauern for about two weeks in March 1965 along with a film crew of around 60 people. Locals served as ski stunt doubles for the Beatles who stayed at the hotel \"Edelweiss\". Most of the crew were based in the hotel \"Marieta\", where one night the Beatles gave an impromptu concert on the occasion of a director's assistant's birthday. This was the only time they ever played on stage in Austria.<ref name=FAS>{{cite news | last =  Kast| first = G\u00fcnter| author2 = | title = Hi-Hi-Hilfe! | newspaper = Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung | location = Travel Section | pages = 4 | language = German | publisher = | date = 4 January 2015 | url = | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\nThe Beatles did not particularly enjoy the filming ''Help!'', nor were they pleased with the end product. In 1970, [[John Lennon]] said they felt like extras in their own film.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Beatles with Eleanor Bron.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Beatles with costar Eleanor Bron.]] -->\n{{quote|text=The film was out of our control. With ''A Hard Day's Night'', we had a lot of input, and it was semi-realistic. But with ''Help!'', Dick Lester didn't tell us what it was all about. |sign=John Lennon on filming ''Help!''}}\n\nTen years later Lennon was more charitable:<ref>Sheff, David.  ''All We Are Saying''. 2000, St Martin's Griffin, {{ISBN|0-312-25464-4}}, p. 176</ref>\n\n{{quote|text=I realize, looking back, how advanced it was. It was a precursor to the [[Batman (TV series)|''Batman'']] \"Pow!  Wow!\" on TV\u2014that kind of stuff. But [Lester] never explained it to us. Partly, maybe, because we hadn't spent a lot of time together between ''A Hard Day's Night'' and ''Help!'', and partly because we were smoking marijuana for breakfast during that period. Nobody could communicate with us, it was all glazed eyes and giggling all the time. In our own world. It's like doing nothing most of the time, but still having to rise at 7&nbsp;am, so we became bored.}}\n\nA contributing factor was exhaustion attributable to their busy schedule of writing, recording and touring. Afterward they were hesitant to begin another film project, and indeed ''Help!'' was their last full-length scripted theatrical film. Their obligation for a third film to United Artists was met by the 1970 documentary film [[Let It Be (film)|''Let It Be'']]. The 1968 animated film ''[[Yellow Submarine (1968 film)|Yellow Submarine]]'' did not meet contractual obligations because it did not star the Beatles, and their only live appearance was featured for less than two minutes at the film's conclusion.\n\n===Inspiration===\nThe Beatles said the film was inspired by the classic [[Marx Brothers]] film ''[[Duck Soup (1933 film)|Duck Soup]]'';<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MRpqWHwLZNoC&pg=PT377 |title=Shout!: The Beatles in Their Generation |page=1377 |isbn=0-7432-5378-7 |year=2011 |last=Norman |first=Phillip |publisher=Simon and Schuster |accessdate=2011-03-08}}</ref> it was also directly satirical of the [[James Bond]] series of films.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_8Ob1bL_ongC&pg=PA102 |page=102 |title=Reading the Beatles: Cultural Studies, Literary Criticism, and the Fab Four |year=2012 |last=Womack |first=Kenneth |author2=Davis, Todd F |isbn=0-7914-8196-4 |publisher=SUNY Press |accessdate=2011-03-08}}</ref> At the time of the original release of ''Help!'', its distributor, [[United Artists]], also held the rights to the Bond series.\n\nThe humour of the film is strongly influenced by the abstract humour of ''[[The Goon Show]]'', in which the director had personal and direct experience in the conversion of the radio format to television, and personal working experience with [[Peter Sellers]] in particular.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HESlHkg_pRoC&pg=PA54 |title=John Lennon Imagined: Cultural History of a Rock Star |page=54 |isbn=0-8204-6788-X |year=2004 |last=M\u00e4kel\u00e4 |first=Janne |publisher=Peter Lang |accessdate=2011-03-08}}</ref> Beatles recording producer [[George Martin]] had also produced records for the ''Goon Show'' team. McCartney has always said that the Beatles style of humour was taken from the ''Goon Show''. Many of the film's concepts are derived from ''Goon Show''s, such as the presence of wild animals, music, [[fourth wall]]-breaking jokes and abstractions such as the closing statement that concludes the film.\n\n===Working title===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2019}}\nThe original working title for the film was ''Eight Arms to Hold You''. This title was printed on the single \"Ticket to Ride\" as an upcoming film. Because of this, the phrase has been used as a title for an album by [[Veruca Salt]] and for songs by [[The Goonies]] and by the Brittles, a Beatles-pastiche band.\n\nThe Lennon-McCartney composition \"[[Eight Days a Week]]\" was briefly considered as a potential theme song for the film, but the idea was scrapped and the song was instead recorded and issued as an album track on ''[[Beatles for Sale]]'', as well as a single in the United States.\n\n===\"Haze of marijuana\"===\nThe Beatles later said the film was shot in a \"haze of marijuana\". According to Starr's interviews in ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'', during the Austrian Alps film shooting, he and McCartney ran off over the hill from the \"[[curling]]\" scene set to smoke a joint.\n{{quote|text=A hell of a lot of pot was being smoked while we were making the film. It was great. That helped make it a lot of fun&nbsp;... In one of the scenes, Victor Spinetti and Roy Kinnear are playing curling: sliding along those big stones. One of the stones has a bomb in it and we find out that it's going to blow up, and have to run away. Well, Paul and I ran about seven miles, we ran and ran, just so we could stop and have a joint before we came back. We could have run all the way to Switzerland. If you look at pictures of us you can see a lot of red-eyed shots; they were red from the dope we were smoking. And these were those clean-cut boys! Dick Lester knew that very little would get done after lunch. In the afternoon we very seldom got past the first line of the script. We had such hysterics that no one could do anything. Dick Lester would say, \"No, boys, could we do it again?\" It was just that we had a lot of fun \u2013 a lot of fun in those days.|sign=Ringo Starr}}\n\nIn the ''Beatles Anthology Director's Cut'', Harrison admitted that they were smoking marijuana on the plane ride all the way to the Bahamas.\n\nMcCartney also shared some of his memories of when they were filming ''Help!'':\n\n{{quote|text=We showed up a bit stoned, smiled a lot and hoped we'd get through it. We giggled a lot. I remember one time at Cliveden (Lord Astor's place, where the [[Profumo affair|Christine Keeler/Profumo scandal]] went on); we were filming the [[Buckingham Palace]] scene where we were all supposed to have our hands up. It was after lunch, which was fatal because someone might have brought out a glass of wine as well. We were all a bit merry and all had our backs to the camera and the giggles set in. All we had to do was turn around and look amazed, or something. But every time we'd turn round to the camera there were tears streaming down our faces. It's OK to get the giggles anywhere else but in films, because the technicians get pissed off with you. They think, \"They're not very professional.\" Then you start thinking, \"This isn't very professional \u2013 but we're having a great laugh.\"|sign=Paul McCartney}}\n\n{{quote|text=John did once offer me a joint. And I obligingly tried to take a little puff. I knew there was some special way of doing it \u2013 but I don't smoke anyway. So I took a little puff and then thought, \"This is so expensive. I mustn't waste it!\"  And gave it back to him. So that's your definition of na\u00efve, I think.|sign=Eleanor Bron}}\n\nThe photographer [[Michael Peto]] was commissioned in 1965 to take still photographs during the making of the film; these became known for their candid and expressive quality. During the digitisation of the Michael Peto Collection, which is held by Archive Services, [[University of Dundee]], in 2002, 500 previously unpublished photographs of the Beatles taken during the making of ''Help!'' were reported to have been uncovered.<ref name=\"Pictures discovered\">{{cite news|title=Rare Beatles pictures discovered|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2304101.stm|accessdate=2 September 2011|newspaper=BBC News|date=7 October 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Beatles photographs\">{{cite news|title=Beatles photographs come to light|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2002/oct/08/thebeatles.highereducation|accessdate=2 September 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 October 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Photos uncovered\">{{cite web|title=Unseen photos of The Beatles uncovered|url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/pressreleases/proct02/beatles.html|publisher=University of Dundee|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Michael Peto\">{{cite web|title=Michael Peto Photographic Collection |url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/peto.htm |publisher=University of Dundee |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903021711/http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/peto.htm |archivedate=3 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''Now These Days are Gone'', a limited edition volume of Peto's photographs focusing on the Beatles images was produced in 2006 with deluxe editions of the book signed by [[Richard Lester]]. An exhibition of the photographs to mark the book's launch was held at Hoopers Gallery, Clerkenwell, in January 2006.<ref name=Archive>{{cite web|title=Help!|url=http://www.archives-records-artefacts.blogspot.com/2010/08/help.html|publisher=Archives, Records and Artefacts at the University of Dundee|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Book launch\">{{cite web|title=Michael Peto Photograph Collection Book/Exhibition Launch |url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/petolaunch.htm |publisher=University of Dundee |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614094455/http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/petolaunch.htm |archivedate=14 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Another exhibition of the photographs was held at the [[University of Dundee]] in 2007 as part of the University's 40th anniversary celebrations, with the exhibition then moving to the National Conservation Centre, [[Liverpool]].<ref name=\"University of Dundee\">{{cite web|title=The Michael Peto Collection and the University of Dundee |url=http://www.computing.dundee.ac.uk/iticse2007/beatles.asp |publisher=[[University of Dundee]] |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321142941/http://www.computing.dundee.ac.uk/iticse2007/beatles.asp |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Liverpool>[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/conservation/exhibitions/beatles/ \"Now These Days Are Gone: The Beatles Photographs of Michael Peto, 18 August 2007 to 2 March 2008\"], National Conservation Centre, National Museums Liverpool, 31 Jul 2007, accessed 5 Sep 2010</ref> In 2011 the photographs were exhibited in Dundee, as part of the Scottish Beatles Weekend, and at the Proud Gallery, [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Alan|title=Rare chance to see Peto Collection photos during Scottish Beatles Weekend|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/Living/Music/article/15780/rare-chance-to-see-peto-collection-photos-during-scottish-beatles-weekend.html|accessdate=2 September 2011|newspaper=The Courier|date=18 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731162547/http://www.thecourier.co.uk/Living/Music/article/15780/rare-chance-to-see-peto-collection-photos-during-scottish-beatles-weekend.html|archivedate=31 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Proud>{{cite web|title=The Beatles: Revolutionary 1965 By Michael Peto |url=http://www.proud.co.uk/exhibition-The-Beatles-Revolutionary-1965-by-Michael-Peto_77.aspx |publisher=Proud Galleries |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926073524/http://www.proud.co.uk/exhibition-The-Beatles-Revolutionary-1965-by-Michael-Peto_77.aspx |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Songs==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Beatles - You're Going To Lose That Girl.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Beatles performing \"[[You're Going to Lose That Girl]]\".]] -->\n\nThe songs played during the film are:\n\n* \"[[Help! (song)|Help!]]\"\n* \"[[You're Going to Lose That Girl]]\"\n* \"[[You've Got to Hide Your Love Away]]\"\n* \"[[Ticket to Ride]]\"\n* \"[[I Need You (Beatles song)|I Need You]]\"\n* \"[[The Night Before (song)|The Night Before]]\" interspersed with excerpts of \"She's A Woman\" (also see below) with an explosion at the end not heard on the Beatles' commercial recordings\n* \"[[Another Girl]]\"\n* \"[[She's a Woman]]\" (heard in the background, on a tape machine, and underground in the Salisbury Plain scene)\n* \"[[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\" titled on the US soundtrack album as \"Another Hard Day's Night\" (played by Indian band and as an instrumental medley of \"A Hard Day's Night\", \"Can't Buy Me Love\", and \"I Should Have Known Better\")\n* \"[[I'm Happy Just to Dance with You]]\" (played by a band during the bike-riding scene)\n* \"[[You Can't Do That]]\" (played as an instrumental during the Austrian Alps sequence)\n* \"[[From Me to You]]\" titled on the US soundtrack album as \"From Me To You Fantasy\" (played as an instrumental during scenes of attempts to remove the ring from Ringo's finger while he sleeps in the Beatles' communal apartment)\n\nThe seven main songs formed the first side of the British release of the [[Help!|album of the same name]]. The second side consisted of other new Beatles songs recorded at the same time or shortly afterwards. The US album, released by Capitol Records, includes the seven film tracks along with instrumental soundtrack songs orchestrated by Ken Thorne.  In addition, the US soundtrack leads off with a hidden track stylized as a satirical \"James Bond Theme\" before the title track, \"Help!\".  Early pressings of the US version of the album ''[[1962\u20131966]]'' include this hidden track banded as \"Help!\", and later pressings, when the UK catalogue was made the official and only catalogue of Beatles albums, omit it.\n\n==Critical response==\nCritical opinion at the time of release was generally positive, but many critics feel that this big budget effort was not as strong as ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]''. [[Leslie Halliwell]] describes it as an {{quote|text=[e]xhausting attempt to outdo ''A Hard Day's Night'' in lunatic frenzy, which goes to show that some talents work best on low budgets. The humour is a frantic cross between ''[[Hellzapoppin' (film)|Hellzapoppin']]'', [[The Goon Show|The Goons]], [[Goofy]], [[Mr. Magoo]] and the shade of [[Monty Python's Flying Circus|Monty Python]] to come. It looks good but becomes too tiresome to entertain.<ref>{{cite book |last=Halliwell |first=Leslie |title=Halliwell's Film and Video Guide |year=1997 |publisher=[[Harper Collins]] |location=London |isbn=0-00-638779-9 |page=338}}</ref>}}\n\n[[AllMovie]]'s Ronnie D. Lankford, Jr. describes it as {{quote|text=...&nbsp;a forerunner to music videos.&nbsp;... [[Richard Lester|Lester]] seemed to find the right tone for ''Help!'', creating an enjoyable portrait of the Beatles and never allowing the film to take itself too seriously. His style would later be co-opted by [[Bob Rafelson|Bob Rafaelson]]{{sic}} for [[the Monkees]]' television series in the '60s and has continued to influence rock musicals like ''[[Spice World (film)|Spice World]]'' in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/cg/avg.dll?p=avg&sql=1:22130~T1 |title=Help! |accessdate=24 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060426195934/http://www.allmovie.com/cg/avg.dll?p=avg |archivedate=26 April 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nIn a contemporary review in ''[[The New York Times]]'' their critic [[Bosley Crowther]] was not impressed: {{quote|text=...&nbsp;It's a fiasco of farcical whimseys that are thrown together in this film\u2014a clutter of mechanical gimmicks and madcap chases.&nbsp;... Funny? Exciting? Different? Well, there's nothing in \"Help!\" to compare with that wild ballet of the Beatles racing across a playground in \"A Hard Day's Night\", nothing as wistful as the ramble of Ringo around London all alone.&nbsp;... The boys themselves are exuberant and uninhibited in their own genial way. They just become awfully redundant and\u2014dare I say it?\u2014dull.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news | last = Crowther | first = Bosley |title =Singers romp through comic adventures | newspaper = The New York Times|date = August 24, 1965| url = https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0CEEDC103CE733A25757C2A96E9C946491D6CF| accessdate = April 6, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n==Novelisation==\n\nA [[novelisation]] entitled ''The Beatles in Help!'' was written by Al Hine and published by [[Dell (publisher)|Dell]] in 1965.\n\nA sequence featuring [[Frankie Howerd]] and [[Wendy Richard]] was filmed but left out of final editing owing to its length. However, the sequence was left in the film novelisation.\n\n==Release history==\nLike ''A Hard Day's Night'', ''Help!'' was originally distributed theatrically by [[United Artists]] \u2013 the company handled distribution from 1965 to the end of 1980. In January 1981, rights to the film reverted from UA to producer Walter Shenson, and the film was withdrawn from circulation.\n\n''Help!'' was released several times in different video formats by MPI Home Video and [[The Criterion Collection]]. A version was released in February 1987 in VHS and Beta through MPI, along with a reissue of ''A Hard Day's Night'' the very same day, and was followed by a special-edition release on 31 October 1995. MPI also issued a CLV laserdisc in 1995 and two releases on DVD, the first as a single DVD release on 12 November 1997 and the second as part of ''The Beatles DVD Collector's Set'' on 8 August 2000.\n\nLaserDisc releases include a Criterion CAV laserdisc and a Voyager CLV laserdisc in 1987, each of which had three pressings. The first pressings had no [[Universal Product Code|UPC]] on the gatefold covers while the other two had the UPC either as a sticker or printed directly on the jacket.\n\nThe film's transfer on the CAV laserdiscs was done correctly so that no blending of frames occurs and thus movements are not blurry. The supplemental section, which, with few exceptions, has never been available on any other home video release, contains the following:\n* original theatrical trailer (which includes deleted scenes)\n* silent home film footage of the film set and of the world premiere\n* still photos, some of which are introduced by text describing the production history of the film\n* posters\n* sheet music\n* record jackets\n* radio ads (on audio during the silent footage)\n* an open interview, originally designed for disc jockeys. By reading prompts on the screen, one can pretend to talk to the Beatles.\n\nIn June 2007, a version of ''Help!'', sub-titled in Korean, became available on Amazon.com. However, by July 2007, all home video versions of the film were pulled from the market because of rights issues involving Apple Corps \u2013 now the full rights holders to the film. The rights issues were eventually resolved and Apple Corps/EMI/Capitol released a new double DVD version with a fully restored image and newly remixed in 2.0 stereo and [[5.1]] [[surround]] sound of the film. This came in standard 2xDVD packaging and 2xDVD deluxe edition box set on 30 October 2007 in the UK and 6 November 2007 in America.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2007/press60.htm |title=Stop worrying&nbsp;... Help! is on the way |publisher=EMI Group Limited |date=4 September 2007 |accessdate=23 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011112028/http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2007/press60.htm |archivedate=2007-10-11}}</ref>  This latest release contains new featurettes, three trailers (one of which is in Spanish), and the aforementioned radio ads carried over from the Criterion LaserDisc issue. The film was released on Blu-ray format in June 2013 by [[Universal Music]], now the owners of EMI/Capitol Records, using the 2007 restoration.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1562341/beatles-help-comes-to-blu-ray | title=Beatles 'Help!' Comes to Blu-Ray | work=Billboard | first=Lars | last=Brandle | date=16 May 2013 | accessdate=23 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=video|artist=The Beatles|title=Help|award=Gold|certyear=2007|salesamount=7,500|access-date=15 September 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|type=video|artist=The Beatles|title=Help|award=Platinum|number=8|relyear=1965|access-date=15 September 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=video|artist=Beatles, The|title=Help!|award=Platinum|number=5|relyear=1965|access-date=15 September 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.thebeatles.com The Beatles]\n*{{IMDb title|0059260|Help!}}\n*{{tcmdb title|77759|Help!}}\n*{{Amg movie|22130|Help!}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|beatles_the_help|Help!}}\n\n{{Help! (album)}}\n{{Richard Lester}}\n{{Beatles filmography and videography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Help! (Film)}}\n[[Category:1960s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1960s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:British chase films]]\n[[Category:Films about the Beatles]]\n[[Category:British rock music films]]\n[[Category:Self-reflexive films]]\n[[Category:Skiing films]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Richard Lester]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Alps]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Austria]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Bahamas]]\n[[Category:Mad scientist films]]\n[[Category:Films about cults]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Help!\n| image          = Helponesheet.jpg\n| image_size     = 225px\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Richard Lester]]\n| producer       = [[Walter Shenson]]\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Marc Behm]]\n* [[Charles Wood (playwright)|Charles Wood]]\n}}\n| story          = Marc Behm\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[The Beatles]]\n* [[Leo McKern]]\n* [[Eleanor Bron]]\n* [[Victor Spinetti]]\n* [[Roy Kinnear]]\n}}\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n* '''Musical Director:'''\n* [[Ken Thorne]]\n* '''Songs:'''\n* [[Lennon-McCartney]]\n* [[George Harrison]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[David Watkin (cinematographer)|David Watkin]]\n| editing        = John Victor-Smith\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* Walter Shenson Films\n* [[Apple Corps|Subafilms]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1965|7|29|UK|1965|8|11|US|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.5 million<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160202000614/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0059260/business Box Office Information for ''Help!''] [[IMDb]] via [[Internet Archive]]. Retrieved June 17, 2018.</ref>\n| gross          = $12.1 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1965/00235.php|publisher=The Numbers|title=Help!, Box Office Information|accessdate=22 January 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Help!''''' is a 1965 British [[Musical film|musical]] [[Comedy film|comedy]]-[[Adventure film|adventure]] film directed by [[Richard Lester]], starring [[the Beatles]]\u2013[[John Lennon]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[George Harrison]] and [[Ringo Starr]]\u2014and featuring [[Leo McKern]], [[Eleanor Bron]], [[Victor Spinetti]], [[John Bluthal]], [[Roy Kinnear]] and [[Patrick Cargill]]. The second film starring the Beatles following Lester's ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'', ''Help!'' sees the group struggle to record their new album while trying to protect Starr from a sinister [[cult]] and a pair of mad scientists, all of whom are obsessed with obtaining one of his rings.<ref name=\"Beatles.com\">{{cite web|title=Help!|url=http://www.beatles.com/#/films/Help|publisher=Beatles.com|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> The soundtrack was released as an album, also called ''[[Help!]]''.\n\nThe film had its Royal World Premiere at the [[London Pavilion]] Theatre in the [[West End of London]] on 29 July 1965 in the presence of [[Princess Margaret]], Countess of Snowdon and the [[Antony Charles Robert Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]]. While not reviewed at the time with the same high level of admiration as their first film, the film is regarded a half century later as being influential, including in the subsequent development of  [[music videos]].\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[File:The Beatles Trailer USHelp.jpg|left|thumb|225x225px|Screenshot of [[the Beatles]] in ''Help!'']]\nAn [[Eastern world|eastern]] [[cult]] (a parody of the [[Thuggee]] cult) is about to sacrifice a woman to the [[goddess]] [[Kali|Kali]]. They notice that she is not wearing the sacrificial ring. Instead, [[Ringo Starr]], drummer of the Beatles, has the ring, sent to him by the victim and her high priestess sister, who are both fans of the Beatles. Determined to retrieve the ring and sacrifice the girl, the great Swami, several cult members and the high priestess leave for London. After failed attempts to steal the ring without Ringo noticing, they confront him in an Indian restarant. Ringo learns that if he be the next sacrifice if he does not give up the ring. However, the ring is stuck and he cannot take it off. The Beatles are chased around London by members of the cult. In a desperate effort to dispose of the ring, the band resorts to the bumbling efforts of a mad scientist and his assistant; when his equipment turns out to have no effect on the ring, the scientist decides that he, too, must somehow acquire it. The band runs to the Swiss Alps and narrowly escapes a trap there, thanks to the help of the high priestess, who is secretly aiding the Beatles. To stay safe, they ask for protection from Scotland Yard.  They hide in Buckingham Palace, narrowly avoiding capture by the scientist. The band runs to the Bahamas, followed by the police officers, the scientist, and the cult members. After Ringo is nearly captured, the other Beatles pose as him in order to lure out the cult members to be arrested by the police. Despite their best efforts, however, Ringo is captured by the scientist, who intends on cutting off his finger to get the ring.  The high priestess rescues Ringo by giving the scientist a shrinking solution in exchange.  The two of them dive into the ocean to escape, but Ringo cannot swim and they are both captured by the great Swami. In the end, when Ringo is about to be sacrificed, the ring suddenly comes off. He puts the ring on the great Swami who is then chased by his own cult.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[John Lennon]]     as himself \n*[[Paul McCartney]]  as himself\n*[[George Harrison]] as himself\n*[[Ringo Starr]]     as himself\n*[[Eleanor Bron]]    as Ahme\n*[[Leo McKern]]      as Clang\n*[[John Bluthal]]    as Bhuta\n*[[Patrick Cargill]] as Superintendent Gluck\n*[[Victor Spinetti]] as Foot\n*[[Roy Kinnear]]     as Algernon\n*[[Alfie Bass]]      as Doorman\n*[[Warren Mitchell]] as Abdul\n*[[Peter Copley]] as Jeweler\n*[[Bruce Lacey]] as Lawnmower\n*Durra as Belly Dancer\n*[[Mal Evans]]       as Channel Swimmer (uncredited)\n*[[Gretchen Franklin]] as Neighbor (uncredited)\n*[[Dandy Nichols]] as Neighbor (uncredited)\n*[[Jeremy Lloyd]] as Restaurant Patron (uncredited)\n*[[John Louis Mansi]] as Priest / Thug\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nAccording to interviews conducted with [[Paul McCartney]], [[George Harrison]], and [[Ringo Starr]] for ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'', director Richard Lester was given a larger budget for this film than he had for ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'', thanks to the commercial success of the latter. Thus, this feature film was in colour and was shot on several exotic foreign locations. It was also given a more extensive musical score than ''A Hard Day's Night'', provided by a full orchestra, and including pieces of well known classical music: [[Wagner]]'s ''[[Lohengrin (opera)|Lohengrin]]'', Act III Overture, [[Tchaikovsky]]'s \"[[1812 Overture]]\", [[Beethoven]]'s \"[[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Ninth Symphony]]\" (\"Ode to Joy\"), and, during the end credits and with their own comic vocal interpretation, [[Rossini]]'s \"[[The Barber of Seville|Barber of Seville]]\" overture. The original title for the film \u2013 only changed to ''Help!'' very near to its release \u2013 was ''Eight Arms To Hold You.''<ref>Matthews, Brian.\"Part 7,\" ''The Beatles Story'' (BBC, 1973).</ref>\n\n''Help!'' was shot in London, [[Salisbury Plain]], the [[Austria]]n [[Alps]], [[New Providence Island]] and [[Paradise Island]] in the Bahamas and [[Twickenham Film Studios]], beginning in the Bahamas on 23 February 1965. Starr commented in ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'' that they were in the Bahamas for the hot weather scenes, and therefore had to wear light clothing even though it was rather cold. Tony Bramwell, the assistant to Beatles manager Brian Epstein, stated in his book ''A Magical Mystery Tour'' that Epstein chose the Bahamas for tax reasons. According to ''The Beatles Anthology'', during the restaurant sequence filmed in early April, George began to discover [[India]]n-style music, which would be a key element in future songs such as [[Norwegian Wood (This Bird Has Flown)|\"Norwegian Wood\"]]. Filming finished on 14 April at Ailsa Avenue in [[Twickenham]].\n\nThe ski scenes were shot at [[Obertauern]], a small village in Austria. One reason this location was chosen was that the stars of the film were less likely to be recognized there than at one of the larger resorts with many British tourists. The Beatles were in Obertauern for about two weeks in March 1965 along with a film crew of around 60 people. Locals served as ski stunt doubles for the Beatles who stayed at the hotel \"Edelweiss\". Most of the crew were based in the hotel \"Marieta\", where one night the Beatles gave an impromptu concert on the occasion of a director's assistant's birthday. This was the only time they ever played on stage in Austria.<ref name=FAS>{{cite news | last =  Kast| first = G\u00fcnter| author2 = | title = Hi-Hi-Hilfe! | newspaper = Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung | location = Travel Section | pages = 4 | language = German | publisher = | date = 4 January 2015 | url = | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\nThe Beatles did not particularly enjoy the filming ''Help!'', nor were they pleased with the end product. In 1970, [[John Lennon]] said they felt like extras in their own film.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Beatles with Eleanor Bron.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Beatles with costar Eleanor Bron.]] -->\n{{quote|text=The film was out of our control. With ''A Hard Day's Night'', we had a lot of input, and it was semi-realistic. But with ''Help!'', Dick Lester didn't tell us what it was all about. |sign=John Lennon on filming ''Help!''}}\n\nTen years later Lennon was more charitable:<ref>Sheff, David.  ''All We Are Saying''. 2000, St Martin's Griffin, {{ISBN|0-312-25464-4}}, p. 176</ref>\n\n{{quote|text=I realize, looking back, how advanced it was. It was a precursor to the [[Batman (TV series)|''Batman'']] \"Pow!  Wow!\" on TV\u2014that kind of stuff. But [Lester] never explained it to us. Partly, maybe, because we hadn't spent a lot of time together between ''A Hard Day's Night'' and ''Help!'', and partly because we were smoking marijuana for breakfast during that period. Nobody could communicate with us, it was all glazed eyes and giggling all the time. In our own world. It's like doing nothing most of the time, but still having to rise at 7&nbsp;am, so we became bored.}}\n\nA contributing factor was exhaustion attributable to their busy schedule of writing, recording and touring. Afterward they were hesitant to begin another film project, and indeed ''Help!'' was their last full-length scripted theatrical film. Their obligation for a third film to United Artists was met by the 1970 documentary film [[Let It Be (film)|''Let It Be'']]. The 1968 animated film ''[[Yellow Submarine (1968 film)|Yellow Submarine]]'' did not meet contractual obligations because it did not star the Beatles, and their only live appearance was featured for less than two minutes at the film's conclusion.\n\n===Inspiration===\nThe Beatles said the film was inspired by the classic [[Marx Brothers]] film ''[[Duck Soup (1933 film)|Duck Soup]]'';<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MRpqWHwLZNoC&pg=PT377 |title=Shout!: The Beatles in Their Generation |page=1377 |isbn=0-7432-5378-7 |year=2011 |last=Norman |first=Phillip |publisher=Simon and Schuster |accessdate=2011-03-08}}</ref> it was also directly satirical of the [[James Bond]] series of films.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_8Ob1bL_ongC&pg=PA102 |page=102 |title=Reading the Beatles: Cultural Studies, Literary Criticism, and the Fab Four |year=2012 |last=Womack |first=Kenneth |author2=Davis, Todd F |isbn=0-7914-8196-4 |publisher=SUNY Press |accessdate=2011-03-08}}</ref> At the time of the original release of ''Help!'', its distributor, [[United Artists]], also held the rights to the Bond series.\n\nThe humour of the film is strongly influenced by the abstract humour of ''[[The Goon Show]]'', in which the director had personal and direct experience in the conversion of the radio format to television, and personal working experience with [[Peter Sellers]] in particular.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HESlHkg_pRoC&pg=PA54 |title=John Lennon Imagined: Cultural History of a Rock Star |page=54 |isbn=0-8204-6788-X |year=2004 |last=M\u00e4kel\u00e4 |first=Janne |publisher=Peter Lang |accessdate=2011-03-08}}</ref> Beatles recording producer [[George Martin]] had also produced records for the ''Goon Show'' team. McCartney has always said that the Beatles style of humour was taken from the ''Goon Show''. Many of the film's concepts are derived from ''Goon Show''s, such as the presence of wild animals, music, [[fourth wall]]-breaking jokes and abstractions such as the closing statement that concludes the film.\n\n===Working title===\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2019}}\nThe original working title for the film was ''Eight Arms to Hold You''. This title was printed on the single \"Ticket to Ride\" as an upcoming film. Because of this, the phrase has been used as a title for an album by [[Veruca Salt]] and for songs by [[The Goonies]] and by the Brittles, a Beatles-pastiche band.\n\nThe Lennon-McCartney composition \"[[Eight Days a Week]]\" was briefly considered as a potential theme song for the film, but the idea was scrapped and the song was instead recorded and issued as an album track on ''[[Beatles for Sale]]'', as well as a single in the United States.\n\n===\"Haze of marijuana\"===\nThe Beatles later said the film was shot in a \"haze of marijuana\". According to Starr's interviews in ''[[The Beatles Anthology]]'', during the Austrian Alps film shooting, he and McCartney ran off over the hill from the \"[[curling]]\" scene set to smoke a joint.\n{{quote|text=A hell of a lot of pot was being smoked while we were making the film. It was great. That helped make it a lot of fun&nbsp;... In one of the scenes, Victor Spinetti and Roy Kinnear are playing curling: sliding along those big stones. One of the stones has a bomb in it and we find out that it's going to blow up, and have to run away. Well, Paul and I ran about seven miles, we ran and ran, just so we could stop and have a joint before we came back. We could have run all the way to Switzerland. If you look at pictures of us you can see a lot of red-eyed shots; they were red from the dope we were smoking. And these were those clean-cut boys! Dick Lester knew that very little would get done after lunch. In the afternoon we very seldom got past the first line of the script. We had such hysterics that no one could do anything. Dick Lester would say, \"No, boys, could we do it again?\" It was just that we had a lot of fun \u2013 a lot of fun in those days.|sign=Ringo Starr}}\n\nIn the ''Beatles Anthology Director's Cut'', Harrison admitted that they were smoking marijuana on the plane ride all the way to the Bahamas.\n\nMcCartney also shared some of his memories of when they were filming ''Help!'':\n\n{{quote|text=We showed up a bit stoned, smiled a lot and hoped we'd get through it. We giggled a lot. I remember one time at Cliveden (Lord Astor's place, where the [[Profumo affair|Christine Keeler/Profumo scandal]] went on); we were filming the [[Buckingham Palace]] scene where we were all supposed to have our hands up. It was after lunch, which was fatal because someone might have brought out a glass of wine as well. We were all a bit merry and all had our backs to the camera and the giggles set in. All we had to do was turn around and look amazed, or something. But every time we'd turn round to the camera there were tears streaming down our faces. It's OK to get the giggles anywhere else but in films, because the technicians get pissed off with you. They think, \"They're not very professional.\" Then you start thinking, \"This isn't very professional \u2013 but we're having a great laugh.\"|sign=Paul McCartney}}\n\n{{quote|text=John did once offer me a joint. And I obligingly tried to take a little puff. I knew there was some special way of doing it \u2013 but I don't smoke anyway. So I took a little puff and then thought, \"This is so expensive. I mustn't waste it!\"  And gave it back to him. So that's your definition of na\u00efve, I think.|sign=Eleanor Bron}}\n\nThe photographer [[Michael Peto]] was commissioned in 1965 to take still photographs during the making of the film; these became known for their candid and expressive quality. During the digitisation of the Michael Peto Collection, which is held by Archive Services, [[University of Dundee]], in 2002, 500 previously unpublished photographs of the Beatles taken during the making of ''Help!'' were reported to have been uncovered.<ref name=\"Pictures discovered\">{{cite news|title=Rare Beatles pictures discovered|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/2304101.stm|accessdate=2 September 2011|newspaper=BBC News|date=7 October 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Beatles photographs\">{{cite news|title=Beatles photographs come to light|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2002/oct/08/thebeatles.highereducation|accessdate=2 September 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|date=8 October 2002}}</ref><ref name=\"Photos uncovered\">{{cite web|title=Unseen photos of The Beatles uncovered|url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/pressreleases/proct02/beatles.html|publisher=University of Dundee|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Michael Peto\">{{cite web|title=Michael Peto Photographic Collection |url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/peto.htm |publisher=University of Dundee |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903021711/http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/peto.htm |archivedate=3 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''Now These Days are Gone'', a limited edition volume of Peto's photographs focusing on the Beatles images was produced in 2006 with deluxe editions of the book signed by [[Richard Lester]]. An exhibition of the photographs to mark the book's launch was held at Hoopers Gallery, Clerkenwell, in January 2006.<ref name=Archive>{{cite web|title=Help!|url=http://www.archives-records-artefacts.blogspot.com/2010/08/help.html|publisher=Archives, Records and Artefacts at the University of Dundee|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Book launch\">{{cite web|title=Michael Peto Photograph Collection Book/Exhibition Launch |url=http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/petolaunch.htm |publisher=University of Dundee |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614094455/http://www.dundee.ac.uk/archives/petolaunch.htm |archivedate=14 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Another exhibition of the photographs was held at the [[University of Dundee]] in 2007 as part of the University's 40th anniversary celebrations, with the exhibition then moving to the National Conservation Centre, [[Liverpool]].<ref name=\"University of Dundee\">{{cite web|title=The Michael Peto Collection and the University of Dundee |url=http://www.computing.dundee.ac.uk/iticse2007/beatles.asp |publisher=[[University of Dundee]] |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321142941/http://www.computing.dundee.ac.uk/iticse2007/beatles.asp |archivedate=21 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Liverpool>[http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/conservation/exhibitions/beatles/ \"Now These Days Are Gone: The Beatles Photographs of Michael Peto, 18 August 2007 to 2 March 2008\"], National Conservation Centre, National Museums Liverpool, 31 Jul 2007, accessed 5 Sep 2010</ref> In 2011 the photographs were exhibited in Dundee, as part of the Scottish Beatles Weekend, and at the Proud Gallery, [[London Borough of Camden|Camden]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Alan|title=Rare chance to see Peto Collection photos during Scottish Beatles Weekend|url=http://www.thecourier.co.uk/Living/Music/article/15780/rare-chance-to-see-peto-collection-photos-during-scottish-beatles-weekend.html|accessdate=2 September 2011|newspaper=The Courier|date=18 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731162547/http://www.thecourier.co.uk/Living/Music/article/15780/rare-chance-to-see-peto-collection-photos-during-scottish-beatles-weekend.html|archivedate=31 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=Proud>{{cite web|title=The Beatles: Revolutionary 1965 By Michael Peto |url=http://www.proud.co.uk/exhibition-The-Beatles-Revolutionary-1965-by-Michael-Peto_77.aspx |publisher=Proud Galleries |accessdate=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926073524/http://www.proud.co.uk/exhibition-The-Beatles-Revolutionary-1965-by-Michael-Peto_77.aspx |archivedate=26 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Songs==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Beatles - You're Going To Lose That Girl.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Beatles performing \"[[You're Going to Lose That Girl]]\".]] -->\n\nThe songs played during the film are:\n\n* \"[[Help! (song)|Help!]]\"\n* \"[[You're Going to Lose That Girl]]\"\n* \"[[You've Got to Hide Your Love Away]]\"\n* \"[[Ticket to Ride]]\"\n* \"[[I Need You (Beatles song)|I Need You]]\"\n* \"[[The Night Before (song)|The Night Before]]\" interspersed with excerpts of \"She's A Woman\" (also see below) with an explosion at the end not heard on the Beatles' commercial recordings\n* \"[[Another Girl]]\"\n* \"[[She's a Woman]]\" (heard in the background, on a tape machine, and underground in the Salisbury Plain scene)\n* \"[[A Hard Day's Night (song)|A Hard Day's Night]]\" titled on the US soundtrack album as \"Another Hard Day's Night\" (played by Indian band and as an instrumental medley of \"A Hard Day's Night\", \"Can't Buy Me Love\", and \"I Should Have Known Better\")\n* \"[[I'm Happy Just to Dance with You]]\" (played by a band during the bike-riding scene)\n* \"[[You Can't Do That]]\" (played as an instrumental during the Austrian Alps sequence)\n* \"[[From Me to You]]\" titled on the US soundtrack album as \"From Me To You Fantasy\" (played as an instrumental during scenes of attempts to remove the ring from Ringo's finger while he sleeps in the Beatles' communal apartment)\n\nThe seven main songs formed the first side of the British release of the [[Help!|album of the same name]]. The second side consisted of other new Beatles songs recorded at the same time or shortly afterwards. The US album, released by Capitol Records, includes the seven film tracks along with instrumental soundtrack songs orchestrated by Ken Thorne.  In addition, the US soundtrack leads off with a hidden track stylized as a satirical \"James Bond Theme\" before the title track, \"Help!\".  Early pressings of the US version of the album ''[[1962\u20131966]]'' include this hidden track banded as \"Help!\", and later pressings, when the UK catalogue was made the official and only catalogue of Beatles albums, omit it.\n\n==Critical response==\nCritical opinion at the time of release was generally positive, but many critics feel that this big budget effort was not as strong as ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]''. [[Leslie Halliwell]] describes it as an {{quote|text=[e]xhausting attempt to outdo ''A Hard Day's Night'' in lunatic frenzy, which goes to show that some talents work best on low budgets. The humour is a frantic cross between ''[[Hellzapoppin' (film)|Hellzapoppin']]'', [[The Goon Show|The Goons]], [[Goofy]], [[Mr. Magoo]] and the shade of [[Monty Python's Flying Circus|Monty Python]] to come. It looks good but becomes too tiresome to entertain.<ref>{{cite book |last=Halliwell |first=Leslie |title=Halliwell's Film and Video Guide |year=1997 |publisher=[[Harper Collins]] |location=London |isbn=0-00-638779-9 |page=338}}</ref>}}\n\n[[AllMovie]]'s Ronnie D. Lankford, Jr. describes it as {{quote|text=...&nbsp;a forerunner to music videos.&nbsp;... [[Richard Lester|Lester]] seemed to find the right tone for ''Help!'', creating an enjoyable portrait of the Beatles and never allowing the film to take itself too seriously. His style would later be co-opted by [[Bob Rafelson|Bob Rafaelson]]{{sic}} for [[the Monkees]]' television series in the '60s and has continued to influence rock musicals like ''[[Spice World (film)|Spice World]]'' in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/cg/avg.dll?p=avg&sql=1:22130~T1 |title=Help! |accessdate=24 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060426195934/http://www.allmovie.com/cg/avg.dll?p=avg |archivedate=26 April 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\n\nIn a contemporary review in ''[[The New York Times]]'' their critic [[Bosley Crowther]] was not impressed: {{quote|text=...&nbsp;It's a fiasco of farcical whimseys that are thrown together in this film\u2014a clutter of mechanical gimmicks and madcap chases.&nbsp;... Funny? Exciting? Different? Well, there's nothing in \"Help!\" to compare with that wild ballet of the Beatles racing across a playground in \"A Hard Day's Night\", nothing as wistful as the ramble of Ringo around London all alone.&nbsp;... The boys themselves are exuberant and uninhibited in their own genial way. They just become awfully redundant and\u2014dare I say it?\u2014dull.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news | last = Crowther | first = Bosley |title =Singers romp through comic adventures | newspaper = The New York Times|date = August 24, 1965| url = https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B0CEEDC103CE733A25757C2A96E9C946491D6CF| accessdate = April 6, 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n==Novelisation==\n\nA [[novelisation]] entitled ''The Beatles in Help!'' was written by Al Hine and published by [[Dell (publisher)|Dell]] in 1965.\n\nA sequence featuring [[Frankie Howerd]] and [[Wendy Richard]] was filmed but left out of final editing owing to its length. However, the sequence was left in the film novelisation.\n\n==Release history==\nLike ''A Hard Day's Night'', ''Help!'' was originally distributed theatrically by [[United Artists]] \u2013 the company handled distribution from 1965 to the end of 1980. In January 1981, rights to the film reverted from UA to producer Walter Shenson, and the film was withdrawn from circulation.\n\n''Help!'' was released several times in different video formats by MPI Home Video and [[The Criterion Collection]]. A version was released in February 1987 in VHS and Beta through MPI, along with a reissue of ''A Hard Day's Night'' the very same day, and was followed by a special-edition release on 31 October 1995. MPI also issued a CLV laserdisc in 1995 and two releases on DVD, the first as a single DVD release on 12 November 1997 and the second as part of ''The Beatles DVD Collector's Set'' on 8 August 2000.\n\nLaserDisc releases include a Criterion CAV laserdisc and a Voyager CLV laserdisc in 1987, each of which had three pressings. The first pressings had no [[Universal Product Code|UPC]] on the gatefold covers while the other two had the UPC either as a sticker or printed directly on the jacket.\n\nThe film's transfer on the CAV laserdiscs was done correctly so that no blending of frames occurs and thus movements are not blurry. The supplemental section, which, with few exceptions, has never been available on any other home video release, contains the following:\n* original theatrical trailer (which includes deleted scenes)\n* silent home film footage of the film set and of the world premiere\n* still photos, some of which are introduced by text describing the production history of the film\n* posters\n* sheet music\n* record jackets\n* radio ads (on audio during the silent footage)\n* an open interview, originally designed for disc jockeys. By reading prompts on the screen, one can pretend to talk to the Beatles.\n\nIn June 2007, a version of ''Help!'', sub-titled in Korean, became available on Amazon.com. However, by July 2007, all home video versions of the film were pulled from the market because of rights issues involving Apple Corps \u2013 now the full rights holders to the film. The rights issues were eventually resolved and Apple Corps/EMI/Capitol released a new double DVD version with a fully restored image and newly remixed in 2.0 stereo and [[5.1]] [[surround]] sound of the film. This came in standard 2xDVD packaging and 2xDVD deluxe edition box set on 30 October 2007 in the UK and 6 November 2007 in America.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2007/press60.htm |title=Stop worrying&nbsp;... Help! is on the way |publisher=EMI Group Limited |date=4 September 2007 |accessdate=23 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011112028/http://www.emigroup.com/Press/2007/press60.htm |archivedate=2007-10-11}}</ref>  This latest release contains new featurettes, three trailers (one of which is in Spanish), and the aforementioned radio ads carried over from the Criterion LaserDisc issue. The film was released on Blu-ray format in June 2013 by [[Universal Music]], now the owners of EMI/Capitol Records, using the 2007 restoration.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1562341/beatles-help-comes-to-blu-ray | title=Beatles 'Help!' Comes to Blu-Ray | work=Billboard | first=Lars | last=Brandle | date=16 May 2013 | accessdate=23 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=video|artist=The Beatles|title=Help|award=Gold|certyear=2007|salesamount=7,500|access-date=15 September 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|type=video|artist=The Beatles|title=Help|award=Platinum|number=8|relyear=1965|access-date=15 September 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=video|artist=Beatles, The|title=Help!|award=Platinum|number=5|relyear=1965|access-date=15 September 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.thebeatles.com The Beatles]\n*{{IMDb title|0059260|Help!}}\n*{{tcmdb title|77759|Help!}}\n*{{Amg movie|22130|Help!}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|beatles_the_help|Help!}}\n\n{{Help! (album)}}\n{{Richard Lester}}\n{{Beatles filmography and videography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Help! (Film)}}\n[[Category:1960s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1960s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:British chase films]]\n[[Category:Films about the Beatles]]\n[[Category:British rock music films]]\n[[Category:Self-reflexive films]]\n[[Category:Skiing films]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Richard Lester]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Alps]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Austria]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Bahamas]]\n[[Category:Mad scientist films]]\n[[Category:Films about cults]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help!_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Athy (Parliament of Ireland constituency)", "text_new": "{{Infobox constituency\n| name = Athy\n| type = \n| constituency_link = List of Irish constituencies\n| parl_name = [[Irish House of Commons]]\n| year = {{Start date|1614}}\n| abolished = 1800\n| next = Disenfranchised\n}}\n\n'''Athy''' was a [[constituency]] represented in the [[Irish House of Commons]] to 1800. Following the [[Act of Union 1800]] the borough was disenfranchised.\n\n==History==\nIn the [[Patriot Parliament]] of 1689 summoned by [[James II of England|King James II]], Athy was represented with two members.<ref>O'Hart (2007), p. 502</ref>\n\n==Members of Parliament, 1560\u20131801==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Election!!!!First member!!First party!!!!Second member!!Second party\n|-\n| 1560\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Richard Mothill<ref name=PP>{{cite book|title=Parliamentary Papers, Volume 62, Part 2|page=619}} </ref>\n| <!-- party -->\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Rowland Cassyn <ref name=PP/> \n| <!-- party -->\n|-\n| 1613\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Walter Weldon<ref name=PP/>\n| <!-- party -->\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Sir [[Robert Digby (courtier)|Robert Digby]]<ref name=MP/>\n| <!-- party -->\n|-\n| 1634\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Sir [[Maurice Eustace (Lord Chancellor)|Maurice Eustace]]<ref name=MP/>\n| <!-- party -->\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Edward Blount<ref name=MP/>\n| <!-- party -->\n|-\n| 1639\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Steven Stephens<ref name=PP/> \n| <!-- party -->\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Sir Robert Meredith <ref name=MP>http://www.tara.tcd.ie/handle/2262/77206</ref>\n| <!-- party -->\n|-\n| 1661\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| William Weldon<ref name=PP/>\n| <!-- party -->\n| style=\"background-color: {{/meta/color}}\" |\n| Henry Brenn <ref na